defaultA level crossing order sets out in general terms how the crossing should be safely operated. 
defaultI 
defaultenclose
default 
defaultcopies of the Level Crossing Order approved in 2013 which replaced and revoked the 1975 Order (as amended in 1976). 
defaultI also attach the draft Orders at the time of the accident. 
defaultORR inspects the industry’s management of level crossings to check that legal safety requirements are being met. Where failings are found, immediate action is taken to ensure the crossing is made safe. 
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultNetwork Rail requested a new updated 
defaultdraft 
defaultOrder in the light of amendments to the Level Crossings Act 1983 brought about by the Road Safety Act 2006, which allows duties on highways authorities to be specified. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAt
default the time of the accident,
default this
default 
defaultdraft
default 
defaultOrder
default 
defaultcontained no fundamental changes to the arrangements then in place under the 1975 Order. At the time of the accident, Network Rail did not comply with the obligations under the 
default1975 
defaultOrder
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultParagraph 3 of the Th
defaultird schedule sets out
default:
default 
default&#xa0;
default“The barriers shall be kept in the raised position except during the time when engines, carriages or other vehicles passing along the railway have occasion to cross the road. The barriers shall be interlocked with the protecting railway signals”. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Crown Prosecution Service 
default(CPS) 
defaultand British Transport Police
default (BTP)
default took the prosecutions of Network Rail and the signaller after the Moreton-on-Lugg accident
default in
default agreement with ORR.
