default As an enforcing authority, ORR has brought forward a number of successful 
defaultprosecutions
default against 
defaultNetwork Rail 
defaultfor breaches of health and safety law and I enclose a list of 
defaultORR enforcement against Network Rail’s controlled infrastructure since April 2006. 
default&#xa0;
defaultNetwork Rail failed to assess the risks and costs properly when they renewed equipment at Moreton-on-Lugg: we collected evidence of this, and would most certainly have p
defaultrosecuted Network Rail for it. 
defaultORR su
defaultbsequently pressed Network Rail to make safety improvements to both this crossing and those at a number of similar locations
default. 
defaultORR's pressure obliged
default Network Rail to retr
defaulto-fit a version of approach locking at around 50 high-risk crossings across the country, which they would not 
defaultnecessarily 
defaulthave done without our intervention.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultThere is nothing in the 1975 Order, which was in force at the time
default of the accident
default, which prevented Network Rail from including an approach locking system and at no stage did ORR approve Network Rail’s decision not to fit approach locking system at Moreton-on-Lugg.  
default&#xa0;
defaultLevel crossing orders do not usually specify details of the functions and interlocking of the equipment, however after the investigations had been completed Network Rail provided a new draft order, which included a 
defaultmore detailed 
defaultspecification for the requirements for approach locking.
default 
defaultThe 2013 Order, which was approved by ORR on behalf of the Secretary of State, includes paragraph 18, which provides the explicit specification for an approach locking device.  
