default&#xa0;default4. Risk assessmentsdefault&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultALCRM is a risk ranking tool used by Network Rail that forms part of their risk assessment. It is not on its own a suitable and sufficient risk assessment. When Network Rail is renewing level crossings we require a suitable and sufficient risk assessment which includes both quantitative and qualitative risk assessments. We expect Network Rail will consider local factors in addition to ALCRM in producing risk assessments at level crossings. We are working with Network Rail who are developing a ‘narrative assessment’ to be used by level crossing managers to ensure that it is a suitable and sufficient risk assessment. 
default&#xa0;defaultIt is for Network Rail to determine the number of crossings in the highest risk classification. Network Rail will provide more details in their draft delivery plan which will be published on 18 December 2013. The final delivery plan will be published on 31 March 2014. 
default&#xa0;defaultOur Strategy is to strive for 
defaultexcellence
default in risk management and control. We do not set a definition of generally acceptable, tolerable and unacceptable fatality probabilities.  We apply the Health and Safety Executive principles of tolerability of risk.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe hold the industry to account through our Health and Safety legislation to enforce against the legal test of reasonable practicability. We are mindful of changing risks. We have to consider safety against convenience to users through level crossing legislation. 
default&#xa0;
defaultW
defaulte inspect the industry’s management of level crossings to check that safety standards are being met. Where failings are found, we have enforcement powers that we use to ensure the crossing is made safe and its management improved.  
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultNetwork Rail uses the ‘level crossing indicator model’ to determine levels of risk reduction in the last control period. This model was verified by our risk assessment specialist who was satisfied with the robustness of the process used. Network Rail is proposing to use the same mode to determine levels of risk reduction for the next control period 2014-19 (CP5).  
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default5. Lidardefault&#xa0;default&#xa0;
defaultWe welcome the development in technology which makes railways safer, however it is for Network Rail as the duty holder to both develop this technology and to ensure that it is being used to manage the risk. 
default&#xa0;
defaultLIDAR is the complementary obstacle detection system at manned controlled barrier with automatic obstacle detection 
defaultcrossings
default (MCB-OD). This type of crossing has automatic full barriers and protecting signals. LIDAR and RADAR (the primary obstacle detection system) prevent trains passing over the crossing until the crossing has been checked and confirmed as being clear from obstacles. LIDAR uses lasers to detect objects and consists of an upper and lower LIDAR. The lower LIDAR scans the crossing at 150mm whilst the upper LIDAR scans at 600mm.
default&#xa0;
defaultNetwork Rail has carried out an assessment to lower LIDAR
default 
defaultin line with their legal duties
default. 
default ORR are currently still evaluating Network Rail’s processes, risk assessments and research documents to evaluate their assumptions that at some level crossings lower LIDAR will not be necessary.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe recognise the concerns that have been raised about crossings with obstacle detection and are keeping them under review.
